{"query": "What are the most and least effective actions for controlling invasive Ponto-Caspian gammarids?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from studies, the most effective actions for controlling invasive Ponto-Caspian gammarids include: dewatering (drying out) the habitat, which killed three species of invasive freshwater shrimp, although one species required water content levels of 4% and below before it was killed (action 1094); certain chemical treatments including iodine solution, acetic acid, Virkon S and sodium hypochlorite, which killed invasive killer shrimp in laboratory conditions, though these were considered impractical for field application (action 1095); changing salinity levels, where one study found that increasing salinity killed the majority of invasive shrimp within five hours (action 1091); and exposure to parasites, where an introduced parasitic mould reduced populations of an invasive shrimp (action 1089). 

The least effective actions include: changing water pH, which did not kill invasive killer shrimp (action 1093); several chemical treatments including methanol, citric acid, urea, hydrogen peroxide and sucrose, which did not kill invasive killer shrimp when added to freshwater (action 1095); and changing salinity, where one study found that increased salinity did not kill invasive killer shrimp (action 1091). 

Several actions had no evidence available including biological control using predatory fish (action 1087), exchanging ballast water (action 1097), cleaning equipment (action 1096), and exposure to disease-causing organisms (action 1090). One action showed limited effectiveness: control movement of gammarids, where movements slowed down or stopped when exposed to predatory fish chemicals, and carbonating water stunned invasive killer shrimp (action 1088).", "action_ids": ["1095","1088","1087","1089","1097","1091","1094","1096","1093","1090"]}

