{
  "query": "How does the effectiveness of altering water salinity compare to altering temperature for controlling invasive invertebrates like Asian clams and Ponto-Caspian gammarids?",
  "relevant_summary": "For Ponto-Caspian gammarids, both salinity and temperature alterations show effectiveness but with different response times. Increasing water salinity killed the majority of invasive shrimp within five hours according to one of two laboratory studies, though one study found increased salinity did not kill invasive killer shrimp (Action ID: 1091). Temperature control showed more consistent results, with water heated to >36\u00b0C killing all shrimps after 15 minutes exposure and >43\u00b0C killing all shrimps immediately (Action ID: 1092). For Asian clams, both methods demonstrated high effectiveness with 100% mortality rates. High salinities (18-34\u2030) achieved 100% mortality of Asian clams in laboratory conditions (Action ID: 1115). Similarly, temperatures of 36\u00b0C or higher killed Asian clams within or after four days (Action ID: 1116). Temperature control appears to achieve faster results for Ponto-Caspian gammarids (15 minutes vs 5 hours), while both methods showed complete effectiveness for Asian clams with temperature requiring a longer exposure period (4 days vs immediate effect of salinity).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1091",
